definition.value: A tertiary amine in which the substituents on nitrogen are benzyl, phenyl and 3-(2-methylpropoxy)-2-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)propyl.
Dicarboxylate anion of D-glucaric acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A glucaric acid anion that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of glucaric acid.
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of ATP; major species present at pH 7.3.
A protochlorophyllide compound having vinyl substituents at the 2- and 4-positions.
An arsenic oxide in which arsenic and oxygen atoms are present in the ratio 2:3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of oxalic acid.
A diamine that is propane substituted by amino groups at positions 1 and 2. Propylenediamine is commonly used as a bidentate ligand in the formation of coordination complexes.
A cyclopentapyran that is 1,4a,5,6,7,7a-hexahydrocyclopenta[c]pyran-4-carboxylic acid substituted at positions 1, 6 and 7 by beta-D-glucosyloxy, hydroxy and methyl groups respectively
A pipecolate that is the conjugate acid of L--pipecolic acid.
